  "response_text": "Here’s a 3-day meal plan focused on heart-healthy choices while incorporating traditional Nigerian staples. This plan emphasizes whole grains, vegetables, lean proteins, and healthy fats.\n\n### Day 1\n**Breakfast:**  \n- Oatmeal made with water or low-fat milk, topped with sliced bananas and a sprinkle of cinnamon.  \n- A small handful of walnuts or almonds for added healthy fats.\n\n**Lunch:**  \n- **Jollof Rice** made with brown rice, tomatoes, bell peppers, onions, and spices.  \n- Grilled chicken breast marinated with herbs and spices.  \n- A side of steamed vegetables (carrots, green beans, or spinach).\n\n**Dinner:**  \n- **Peppered Fish** (using tilapia or mackerel) grilled with spices.  \n- A side of **Efo Riro** (vegetable soup) made with spinach, peppers, and onions.  \n- Serve with a small portion of **Fufu** (preferably made from whole grain, such as cassava or plantain).\n\n### Day 2\n**Breakfast:**  \n- Smoothie made with unsweetened yogurt, spinach, banana, and a tablespoon of ground flaxseed.  \n- A slice of whole-grain bread with avocado spread.\n\n**Lunch:**  \n- **Beans and Plantain Porridge** (Ewa Riro) with a mix of black-eyed peas and ripe plantains cooked with onions and spices.  \n- A side salad with tomatoes, cucumbers, and a drizzle of olive oil and lemon juice.\n\n**Dinner:**  \n- **Okra Soup** made with fresh okra, tomatoes, and lean protein (chicken or fish).  \n- Served with a small portion of **Amala** (made from whole cassava or yam flour) or brown rice.\n\n### Day 3\n**Breakfast:**  \n- Whole grain **Puff-Puff** made with whole wheat flour, served with a side of fruit (like mango or papaya).  \n- A cup of green tea or hibiscus tea (Karkade).\n\n**Lunch:**  \n- **Nkwobi** (cow foot dish) made with a lean cut and a light sauce (use less palm oil).  \n- Served with a side of **Ugu** (pumpkin leaf) sautéed with onions and spices.\n\n**Dinner:**  \n- **Bitter Leaf Soup** (Ofe Onugbu) made with lean meat (like chicken) and served with a small portion of **Semovita** or **Eba**.  \n- A side of steamed mixed vegetables (carrots, green beans, and bell peppers).\n\n### Snacks (for any day)\n- Fresh fruits (like oranges, apples, or guava).\n- A small handful of nuts (almonds or cashews).\n- Cucumber or carrot sticks with a homemade spicy dipping sauce.\n\n### Additional Tips:\n- Use healthy cooking methods like grilling, steaming, or baking instead of frying.\n- Choose lean protein sources and limit the use of red meats.\n- Incorporate as many colorful vegetables in your meals as possible.\n- Stay hydrated with plenty of water, herbal teas, or infused water with fruits.\n\nFeel free to adjust the portion sizes based on your dietary needs and preferences!",
